definition.value: A chemical role played by any unwanted chemical substance inside a confined amount of liquid, gas, or solid, which differs from the chemical composition of the material or compound. For example, an impurity can be an undesired by-product of a chemical reaction or manufacturing process, a drug contaminant, or can be created upon degradation during storage.
An agent that destroy spermatozoa in the male genitalia and block spermatogenesis.
A cardiovascular drug that prevents atherosclerosis (a disease in which the inside of an artery narrows due to the build up of plaque). Compare with antiatherogenic agent.
Any substance that produces or enhances dream-like states of consciousness.

A reagent used in electron paramagnetic resonance (EPR) spectroscopy to react covalently with radical products whose half-life is be too short to detect. The resulting adducts are more stable enabling their paramagnetic resonance spectra to be obtained.
Any agent that induces nausea and vomiting.
Any compound that exhibits antagonist activity at the kappa-opioid receptor.
A substance which is poisonous to fish and is primarily used to eliminate dominant species of fish in water.
Any insecticide that is capable of killing egg cells.
An antiparasitic agent which is effective against amoeba, a genus of single-celled amoeboids in the family Amoebidae.
Any compound that supports healthy aging, slows the biological aging process, or extends lifespan.
A beta-D-glucan in which the glucose units are connected by (1->4) linkages.
a group of substances that bind to a receptor to change that receptor's response to stimulus.
Any receptor modulator acting on sigma receptors.
A sigma receptor modulator that activates the sigma-2 receptor.
A class of diuretics which promote aquaresis (the excretion of water without electrolyte loss).
A drug used to treat myopathy.
A substance used to destroy pests of the subclass Acari (mites and ticks).
A substance that prevents pests from feeding.
A substance that opposes oxidation or inhibits reactions brought about by dioxygen or peroxides.
An insecticide compound naturally occurring in plants.
A substance intended to sterilize any organism.
Any constitutionally or isotopically distinct atom, molecule, ion, ion pair, radical, radical ion, complex, conformer etc., identifiable as a separately distinguishable entity.
A herbicide which when sprayed or dusted on plants causes its leaves to fall off.

Any substance which when absorbed into a living organism may modify one or more of its functions. The term is generally accepted for a substance taken for a therapeutic purpose, but is also commonly used for abused substances.
A substance used to destroy fungal pests.
A substance used to destroy plant pests.
A growth regulator that inhibits the life cycle of an insect.
Strictly, a substance intended to kill members of the class Insecta.  In common usage, any substance used for preventing, destroying, repelling or controlling insects.
A substance used to destroy pests of the phylum Nematoda (roundworms).
A class of neuro-active insecticides that act at the nicotinic acetylcholine receptor.
A substance that increases the efficacy of a pesticide.
Strictly, a substance intended to kill pests. In common usage, any substance used for controlling, preventing, or destroying animal, microbiological or plant pests.
An endogenous molecular entity that results in a colour of an organism as the consequence of the selective absorption of light.
